Technical Architecture Specification: Distributed DAG-Based CI/CD Engine

1. Executive Abstract and System Vision

Modern enterprise CI/CD requirements have outpaced the capabilities of monolithic orchestration tools. To achieve high-velocity delivery, organizations require a specialized engine capable of managing complex dependency chains with granular control over concurrency and fault tolerance. This specification defines a distributed, Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) based engine that decouples workflow logic from execution. By architecting a custom DAG engine rather than relying on off-the-shelf monoliths, we eliminate the head-of-line blocking common in shared-resource environments and provide the deterministic execution necessary for large-scale build pipelines.

The core engineering philosophy of this system is "Infrastructure-Aware but Logic-Independent." The system is designed to thrive within Kubernetes, leveraging its container management capabilities, but its logical integrity is self-contained. The engine treats the underlying orchestration layer as volatile; it recognizes that while Kubernetes can restart a container, it cannot resolve a logical stall in a build pipeline or recover a stateful task dependency. Consequently, the system maintains its own state machine and recovery protocols, providing a robust layer of business-logic resilience that survives infrastructure-level disruptions.

This vision is realized through a strictly decoupled microservice architecture, where high-level scheduling and heavy compute execution are isolated to prevent resource starvation.


